replyContent: Thank you for your feedback! Unfortunately the ISO and shutter speed must be either both auto or both manual, that is a limitation of the device and there is no way around that. However the minimum shutter speed is a really good idea, we'll consider implementing that! By the way, in principle the intervalometer already dims the screen when running.

This app may give you more control than your internal camera but dont count on it. The exposure compensation,white balance and focus modes work fine but the manual ISO setting does nothing. Go to settings/viewfinder/viewfinder overlays and check, /show camera parameters/. Now go back to the camera and choose an ISO number then take a photo. The shutter speed and ISO number the camera used will now appear at the top of your screen. For me the ISO number displayed is always different from the ISO I entered manually. Obviously the app is using auto ISO and ignoring your manual entry. In effect what this means is that the only control you have in choosing exposure is the two steps of exposure correction that can be made using that function. I now have other apps that allow me to set ISO and shutter speed so I know my phone has those capabilities. I would be very hesitant to pay for this app unless you know its working as advertised. What I like about this app is that the controls are at the bottom and to one side of the screen. Other apps crowd too many functions into the area of the shutter button and the icons tend to be small and hard to see which makes settings hard to fine tune.

replyContent: Regarding the bracketing, you can set the volume keys to increase/decrease the number of bracketed photos. Go to Settings / General camera settings tab / Volume keys function, and select "Bracketing increase/decrease frames". When you go down to "1", it automatically disables bracketing. When you go up from 1, it enable it. With EV you can shift it

While on my earlier phones this app produced a near-stock or identical quality to stock camera photos, regarding compression and raw quality, if nothing it provided a few more manual steps in your hands to control. But now on my current phone, the OnePlus 3T, it provides a way better photo quality, I would even say uncomparable. It is probably due to terribly bad compression that OnePlus stock camera creates, making photos appear extremely washed out and without any texture to surfaces. Photos that come out of FV-5 are always almost double the size when you set JPG quality at 100%. And don't be fooled, it's not just about numbers. When you zoom in exactly the same scenes taken with two cameras, photos from FV-5 have plenty more details preserved, and due to much lower compression and noise reduction, surfaces have the natural grainy textures and appear much more natural. I used this app on 99% of my vacation photos, with only exception being night photos as this camera don't have any fancy HDR or night shot algorhytms. Yes, there are bugs not related to photo quality, and also viewfinder interface could use some overhaul, but all in all an amazing camera app.

replyContent: We are currently working on a solution, but in the meantime, you can enable the option in Settings / General camera settings tab (2nd from the top) / Compatibility / Force usage of legacy camera driver. The AF should work reliably, and the resolution should go up to 23 MP. This is actually a bug from Sony to third party apps who want manual control

replyContent: If you setup the intervalometer together with bracketing, it is normal that you get more photos: you will get exactly N x B photos (N = intervalometer shots, B = number of bracketed shots). Regarding the exposure not changing: you need to activate Settings > General camera settings > Pause between exposures, and set Pause duration to Long.

I got this app to replace the original camera app on my phone, which only took blurry images. This app is great for photos, but the consistent bugs really kill it.  One of the major issues I have is, if you leave the camera app open and your screen locks (no third party locks, just the standard phone lock), your phone becomes unusable if you attempt to unlock it. The phone rapidly switches back and forth between the camera app and lock screen. The flash comes on and stays on continuously. The only way to stop the rapid back and forth between app and lock screen is to hold down the power button and do a reset.  A second issue is the random crashing of the app once a photo is taken or when attempting to take a photo. The app will also stay open in the background causing immense battery drain and the phone to get hot.  I've had this app for many months now but it is time to find something better. The bugginess is not worth the missed photo opportunity and frustration.

replyContent: You don't have aperture control on any phone because the camera module simply does not have any mechanical aperture control nor blades to control the aperture (more on this here: http://www.camerafv5.com/faq.php#aperture). You have indeed manual shutter speed, for that you need Oxygen 2.1.1 or higher. Please update your phone to get access to that.

Even with my sound turned off, my phone still vibrates when I take a picture. The developer said this was because of how my ROM interacted with camera shutter sound options. However, none of the other cameras I have used (stock, google, camerazoom, snap camera) vibrate when I have shutter turned off.    2. The PNG option is supposedly an uncompressed format. While the phone file sizes are larger, I did a comparison of various photos and saw no actual improvement of the PNG files over the JPEG versions. I took the exact same shots in the exact same light.   Once I get my new phone (upgrading from a GS3 to a GS5), I will run the app through more tests and see what improvements, if any, are apparent.

For a "powerful" camera app this should never happen. Set to ISO 3200 and it still uses 1/17th shutter speed, which is a shutter speed that should never be an option unless shooting long exposure. Every one of my indoor shots is a blur. Please explain how to control shutter speed or I will be asking for a refund. Crazy how no android app can deal with motion blur issues. I already miss my iPhone.
replyContent:
If despite setting ISO 3200 you are still getting an exposure time of 1/17s it means that it is actually needed in order to get a decent exposure (the scene should be relatively dark). The only option would be applying negative exposure compensation. Given the aperture is fixed, there's nothing the app can do to do it better..
support@camerafv5.com

replyContent: Actually, this was working fine with Android 5, but when Google updated the Nexus 6 to Android 5.1, they removed support for exposure compensation, required for exposure bracketing. replyContent: The bracketing mode uses exposure compensation to produce images with different exposure time. Since the camera will automatically override the exposure time, there's no point on using the speed priority mode, as both things are completely incompatible in purpose. If you still want a refund, please contact us to support@camerafv5.com.

replyContent: RAW images are never shown in the gallery, regardless of the app you use. Android gallery simply does not recognize DNG RAW images. It does not mean they are not there! Just use the Samsung's file manager to browse to Device storage/DCIM/100_CFV5 and you will find the DNG images there. You need an app or a PC to convert DNG images or process them.

replyContent: You can indeed adjust ISO, but not in Program mode (P). As things are working internally, ISO and exposure time but be set either both to automatic, or both manual. Therefore, in program mode (automatic exposure) ISO is not available. When you switch to Shutter speed priority (S) mode, the ISO parameter will be enabled.

Despite the nice advertisements, Camera FV-5 has several issues that are part of the design. I am using it on Nexus 5.  - eats battery like grazy; the back of the phone immediately heats up when the application starts; the battery charge indicator plummets down - there are P and S modes, but the 'auto' S (shutter priority) mode was changed to default back to P in the newest release - the S mode does does *not* work like S mode normally; yes, you can adjust exposure but the ISO value is fixed to a manual; the 'auto ISO' setting does not work at all --> this mode is actually an M (manual) mode with only the exposure time selectable - the exposure time must be pressed to activate the S mode; this is a bug in the newest release - the 'refocus before exposure' pulls typically the manually set focus off even if the camera is not moved, resulting in wrong focus - there is no functional mode that would allow you to set the ISO and automatically adjust the exposure (this is normally called the S mode) - the exposure indicator is not set correctly; when you open the exposure control, the control dial is shown at maximum (1/8000) always even if this is not actually the exposure

For at least Nikon and Canon point-and-shoots, you can point the camera at a gray plastic card, and basically tell it, this is equal red, green, and blue, and subsequent pictures will be corrected using that info. Usually caused by fluorescent lights.  I returned that phone to Verizon and got a Droid Turbo, and was still frustrated with the built in app, and said, hey, didn't I buy FV-5, lets give it a try.  Do yourself a favor and go to their website and read the manual. One of the things I learned is that almost all smart phones do not have an iris, so you can't reduce the iris (is that F-Stop) to increase the things that are in focus Aperture or Av mode.. Also found out I could change the file naming convention to be similar to that of Motorola IMG_<date>_<time>. I also found out that I goofed and picked some strange focus method, the second icon on the left, I was able to put it back to AF auto focus.

content: There are a zillion camera apps, but if you take your photography seriously, Camera FV-5 is the only one worth having. Real exposure and focus control combined with the ability to save in the virtually lossless .png format turns an adequate phone camera into a piece of equipment that will produce gallery quality results. If images mean more to you than the usual weekend snapshots, get this app, apply your brain and eye and a little patience, and make something you can really be proud of. (Later) I'm not sure people understand the value of being able to shoot in the .png format. Without any compression, pictures are free of the .jpg artifacts and degraded resolution that kill the sharpness on most cameras. If this little app did NOTHING else (and it does a lot!), making .png available on a phone would be worth the price. Sure the files are big, but if you're looking for quality from a phone camera, this is how you get it. Turn on the .png format, transfer your pictures to your PC by usb/wire, and you'll see this app's real strength.

replyContent: This is indeed supported by Camera FV-5, but the camera hardware has to support this as well. If available, you will see a "hand" icon on the light metering modes toolbar. Otherwise, the app has detected that the camera does not support this. Unfortunately, nothing can be made to make up for the missing hardware required to make this possible.

content: The histogram freezes randomly (this is being fixed acc. to the developer). The WB presets use the phone's internal algorithms and mess up the result. The "sunny" preset (I have an HTC One) in the app adds so much chromatic aberration as to make the image useless.  The interface is good though, and mimics a DSLR's LCD panel.
replyContent: About the WB results, the ISP (Image Signal Processor) of the camera is to blame and not Camera FV-5, as it is the ISP of the HTC One which is actually doing the white balancing. The chromatic aberration might have to do with a saturation of an individual color channel, introducing false colors. You might need to use negative EV to avoid this.

Camera FV-5 is an excellent camera app that allows tons of control that you just can't get with standard camera apps.  I can do most of what I use my DSLR for on my phone now. Am I exaggerating? No. Some of the features include: slow shutter speed panning, exposure lock and spot metering, exposure compensation, manual ISO control, PRE-FOCUS!!! That last one is my favorite. Think of it as the digital version of "zone focusing" and turn off focus confirmation. Instant picture taking!  I'm using this on a Galaxy Note 3 and it works flawlessly. Kudos to the devs for taking some weight off my neck.  I would like to see an option to focus via long press, and then being able to take a picture by tapping anywhere on the screen.

replyContent: For tripods, ebay.com is a good source for inexpensive "mounts" and "holders" (those are the keywords) for almost any device. Geotagging is already there! Works well but definitely some downfalls will keep me using the stock camera for now. The bracketing will not drop to or below -1. It will get darker but at -1 it brightens back up to 0. By default I usually take slightly dark photos and then post-process brighten them so this is a problem. Next, the stock camera has some built in noise-reduction when shooting at high ISOs, called "Smart Stabilization" which I rely on sometimes. Lastly, the camera doesn't rotate with the screen fully. It will go 90-counterclock but not 90-clockways. One of the nicer features is the use of the volume keys as focus and shutter but with this rotation issue, these keys are on the bottom-left and can't be used how much cameras are: with your right index finger.  Besides these issues, I like the manual control of ISO and the option to have a 1-2 second shutter manually. The longer shutter (60s) actually blends together many pictures and reduces the image size from 12.1MP to about 2MP.  Nice app but it has some things to fix. If you're here because you want real shutter control, aperture control, manual settings, you need a real camera. If you have a mobile phone, stick to stock.

content: ...would be better if I could save higher than 72 dpi. Is there a setting for this I'm missing? Would elevate my rating. Zoom kinda sucks too compared to Pro HDR
replyContent: The DPI is just a tag used for printing, and you can override it with any value you want before printing. The app takes photos at your phone maximum resolution, in your case 4128x3096 pixels, and that is what matters. You are confusing pixels with DPI. Regarding digital zoom, all are the same, since it uses extrapolation. See http://bit.ly/iGKxgG

replyContent: Does the focus rectangle turn into red when you try to take a photo? That means that focus didn't succeed. It might be due to lack of autofocus or because the subject lacks texture and couldn't be focused. You can tell Camera FV-5 to take photos anyway by activating Settings / General camera settings > Allow taking a photo without focus.

I can enlarge these pictures w/o loss of detail. Not as good as my $3k Nikon, but twice as good as any other app I tried.

Might be another common hardware limitation. Allows ISO settings from 100-1600 in jumps of x2 (i.e. 100, 200, 400, 800, 1600), but my tablets camera can go as low as 50. While the auto ISO mode made good use of this, I would appreciate seeing this get a little more flexible as far as user input goes. A little un-responsive, some short delay between pressing an option button and the relevant 'pop up' menu appearing. Nothing patience can't fix. Once again, might be a hardware thing (processor speeds not quite up to i7 standards in tablets, and all that). There is more to it than that - it's all in the dev's description.  5/5 - everything I wanted in my camera presented at a low cost. Definitely worth the investment, even if all you want is to set your own shutter speed!

I think this app has the potential to be the best android camera app. However, several bugs currently prevent it from realizing that potential. I would gladly give this 5 stars but for the following:  * rapid battery drain (on Atrix 2): much worse than any other app, camera or otherwise;   The drain persists even if you turn the phone off (without quitting the app first). Running the   app with max screen brightness exacerbates the drain, but even at low brightness, the drain   is significant.  * metering mode has no effect (Atrix 2, Iconia A500).  * "widescreen viewfinder" option has no effect (Atrix 2, Iconia A500)  * cannot disable shutter sound (unlike other camera apps)  Other things I'd like to see:  * show shutter speed before (not after) taking photo  * show thumbnail of just-taken photo  I've contacted the developer about the first two items, and he returned my emails promptly, but I have heard nothing since. I hope he will continue refining this very promising app.
As a professional photographer I do appreciate your job guys! The programme is really good and user friendly.  Thanks, Alex Efimoff

I have just bought this application, and have some issues with it: The biggest drawback: PNG is not a RAW format. Quality is identical to the best JPEG.  Why would resolution be reduced during long exposures? There are only four white balance presets, and no custom white balance. Exposure compensation is tiny, to almost nothing.  Camera Zoom FX, which was free app, has more "money" value. IMHO.

First, I should say that the controls (like a real stand-alone camera) are very handy.  I also like the total lack of bloat (like special effects, etc.)  I did a comparison by shooting a photo of wide dynamic range with low lighting with three different apps: the native camera app (in a Galaxy Note), Camera FV-5, and HDR Camera+.  The clarity and exposure for the native camera and the FV-5 were about the same.  HDR Camera+ brought up the darkest areas, but had less clarity than FV-5.  However, I would not claim this is a scientific comparison.  The beauty of Camera FV-5 in my view is all the easy-to-access camera controls, without the fluff.

Would be nice of developer added the ability to review past pictures within the app.  Picture quality is the best I've seen yet on my phone.  But still is not even close to an Apple iPhone camera.
I like handy controls like having EV compensation in volume keys for quick access. I like the histogram too. It only lacks some device support for all features.

I never leave reviews. I mean it. But I'm an avid photographer and I have never used an app as amazing as this one. I wish I could change aperture but oh well. you have control over iso, long exposure and more. The quality image that it exports is good enough to look like an iPhone. The only downside is a small lag but that's irrelevant. this is a must have for photographers.

If you know your way around an SLR and do your own post-production work, this app is a MUST HAVE.  Personally, I loath mobile phone cameras.  They're just....awful.  But what they lack in quality they make up for in presence.  Mine is with me all the time.  If I forget my SLR I usually have my pocket camera.  A manual, RAW shooting pistol.   But what if I forget that?!  Camera phone.  Yuk.  But you CAN take passable shots with a camera.  Especially if you can capture full-res and edit in post.  There are a lot of wonderful..."fun"....camera apps out there for iOS and Android.  But if you want to get the most out of your capture device and produce the best pictures you can with post...well...welcome to FV-5.  If you own any HDR software for PC/Mac....Photoshop CS5/6...or Nik HDRefex...or Unified Color Tech... then FV-5 is for you!  User defined braketing!!!!  Awesome.  This app needs some refinements:  Controls should orientate with the phone; External buttons (inc. power) should be user assigned; user interface DOES need to be improved (icons far too large).  However, I'll pay the money to encourage this developer.  The first to finally get what photogs need!
If u are a serious photog. Get it. Perfect on Bionic.
